it's not commercial.

262
00:10:34,466 --> 00:10:36,368
You're an expert
on publishing?

263
00:10:36,401 --> 00:10:38,436
No, I just
know what I write.

264
00:10:38,470 --> 00:10:41,774
One of our poets
is getting six figures

265
00:10:41,807 --> 00:10:44,643
to do a basketball shoe
commercial.

266
00:10:44,676 --> 00:10:46,112
How good are you?

267
00:10:47,846 --> 00:10:48,847
Really good.

268
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:50,314
But it doesn't mean shit,

269
00:10:50,348 --> 00:10:52,617
'cause nobody's interested
in hearing it, anyway.

270
00:10:52,651 --> 00:10:55,988
I'm extremely
interested.

271
00:10:56,021 --> 00:10:58,357
Why don't you meet
me after work?

272
00:11:05,697 --> 00:11:07,933
Here's my portfolio.

273
00:11:07,966 --> 00:11:09,602
Are you serious?

274
00:11:24,182 --> 00:11:25,784
Wait, wait, wait,
not that one.

275
00:11:25,817 --> 00:11:27,519
Oh.

276
00:11:27,552 --> 00:11:29,288
I wrote that
after my brother...

277
00:11:31,690 --> 00:11:34,560
Uh, it's just the first poem
I ever wrote.

278
00:11:34,593 --> 00:11:36,462
It's whatever.

279
00:11:43,401 --> 00:11:45,871
You're not going
to be hovering, are you?

280
00:11:45,904 --> 00:11:46,905
Uh, no.

281
00:11:48,440 --> 00:11:50,476
I'm going to go to the store.
Do you want anything?

282
00:11:50,509 --> 00:11:51,944
Mm-mmm.

283
00:11:55,247 --> 00:11:56,515
[Door opens]

284
00:12:07,826 --> 00:12:09,394
Jake. What's up,
my friend?

285
00:12:09,427 --> 00:12:10,395
Hey, ralphie.

286
00:12:10,428 --> 00:12:12,297
You want a &quot;Vagenmaster&quot;?

287
00:12:12,330 --> 00:12:14,833
Yeah,
but it's &quot;Jagermeister.&quot;

288
00:12:14,866 --> 00:12:16,367
&quot;jagermeister&quot;.

289
00:12:16,401 --> 00:12:17,669
I call it
vagenmaster.

290
00:12:17,702 --> 00:12:19,404
What's the big deal?

291
00:12:19,437 --> 00:12:20,806
All right.

292
00:12:20,839 --> 00:12:22,541
It's 5.99.
What's this?

293
00:12:22,574 --> 00:12:24,443
[Laughs]
That's not money.

294
00:12:24,476 --> 00:12:26,411
Come on, man.
That's just papers.

295
00:12:26,444 --> 00:12:28,213
No, no. I gotcha.

296
00:12:28,246 --> 00:12:29,615
Here you go.
Here you go.

297
00:12:29,648 --> 00:12:31,850
All right.
I'll see you later.

298
00:12:31,883 --> 00:12:32,885
Hang ten.

299
00:12:32,918 --> 00:12:34,687
You always pissed off?

300
00:12:36,988 --> 00:12:39,258
Just be happy you got out
of bed and took a breath.

301
00:12:39,291 --> 00:12:41,794
Yeah, well, maybe your life's
all happy and shit

302
00:12:41,827 --> 00:12:43,128
'cause you got a good job,

303
00:12:43,161 --> 00:12:45,329
but the rest of the world
is in the toilet, as I see it.

304
00:12:45,363 --> 00:12:47,599
So, basically,
you have two emotions,

305
00:12:47,632 --> 00:12:49,601
anger and sarcasm.

306
00:12:49,634 --> 00:12:52,404
Sarcasm's not an emotion.

307
00:12:52,437 --> 00:12:54,173
Afraid of your own heart?

308
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:56,509
Heh.

309
00:12:58,410 --> 00:13:01,113
No. I just wish people
would listen, that's all.

310
00:13:01,146 --> 00:13:03,314
You need
to market yourself.

311
00:13:03,348 --> 00:13:04,817
Enter the poetron slam.

312
00:13:04,850 --> 00:13:05,984
Slams are obviously
not my thing.

313
00:13:06,017 --> 00:13:08,620
I mean, that guy won
with a joke sex poem.

314
00:13:08,653 --> 00:13:10,055
Is that what that was?

315
00:13:10,088 --> 00:13:11,456
The slam's in town.

316
00:13:11,489 --> 00:13:13,091
You have nothing to lose.

317
00:13:13,124 --> 00:13:15,627
I don't need to win any
spoken word races, thanks.

318
00:13:15,660 --> 00:13:17,329
Think of it
as a career move.

319
00:13:17,362 --> 00:13:19,598
There's paychecks
and pensions in poetry now?

320
00:13:19,631 --> 00:13:21,867
I didn't--
I didn't know.

321
00:13:21,900 --> 00:13:23,802
I'm going to a reading.

322
00:13:23,835 --> 00:13:25,938
You interested?

323
00:13:25,971 --> 00:13:27,673
David: This poem is called

324
00:13:27,706 --> 00:13:29,641
<i> things to do
at a poetry reading</i>

325
00:13:29,674 --> 00:13:33,645
<i> when you like a poem,
but nobody else is clapping,</i>

326
00:13:33,678 --> 00:13:35,747
<i> and you don't
want to be the only one.</i>

327
00:13:35,780 --> 00:13:37,415
Try to look moved.

328
00:13:37,449 --> 00:13:39,651
Nod encouragement.

329
00:13:39,684 --> 00:13:40,718
Sigh.

330
00:13:40,752 --> 00:13:43,655
Say, &quot;Hmm.&quot;

331
00:13:43,688 --> 00:13:46,124
try to look very moved.

332
00:13:46,157 --> 00:13:48,026
Sneak around and ask
some of the other people

333
00:13:48,059 --> 00:13:49,895
whether or not
they like the poet.

334
00:13:49,928 --> 00:13:51,463
And if they do,

335
00:13:51,496 --> 00:13:55,934
make a pact to clap after
the next poem, good or bad.

336
00:13:55,967 --> 00:13:57,769
Giggle.

337
00:13:57,802 --> 00:13:58,770
Guffaw.

338
00:13:58,803 --> 00:14:00,873
[Sniffs] Sniffle. Sob.

339
00:14:00,906 --> 00:14:02,840
Wail!

340
00:14:02,874 --> 00:14:05,177
Shift in your chair,

341
00:14:05,210 --> 00:14:08,881
crossing, re-crossing
your shapely thighs.

342
00:14:08,914 --> 00:14:11,917
Take off your shirt
and wave it at the poet,

343
00:14:11,950 --> 00:14:13,952
like a welcome home.

344
00:14:13,985 --> 00:14:16,855
Sing<i> you light up my life.</i>

345
00:14:16,888 --> 00:14:18,390
♪ That I want you ♪

346
00:14:18,423 --> 00:14:19,858
♪ I need you ♪

347
00:14:19,891 --> 00:14:23,562
♪ I luh-huh-huh-
huh-huh-huh-ove you ♪

348
00:14:23,595 --> 00:14:27,165
Drag in marble block
and sculpt the poet.

349
00:14:27,198 --> 00:14:30,936
Pull out a volume of
Shakespeare's complete works

350
00:14:30,969 --> 00:14:33,372
and scratch out
Shakespeare's name

351
00:14:33,405 --> 00:14:35,240
and write in the poet's.

352
00:14:35,273 --> 00:14:38,510
Transcribe the Bible
onto a floppy disk.

353
00:14:38,543 --> 00:14:41,346
While using the &quot;Search
and replace&quot; Command,

354
00:14:41,379 --> 00:14:45,184
substitute the poet's name
for god.

355
00:14:55,327 --> 00:14:57,129
You can learn
a lot from him.

356
00:14:57,162 --> 00:14:58,931
What?
How to be an actor?

357
00:14:58,964 --> 00:15:01,800
He won the poetron slam
last year.

358
00:15:01,833 --> 00:15:03,168
I don't care what he won.

359
00:15:03,201 --> 00:15:04,903
That guy is begging
for applause.

360
00:15:04,936 --> 00:15:06,505
He's promoting his book.

361
00:15:06,538 --> 00:15:08,273
You're working
in a warehouse.

362
00:15:08,306 --> 00:15:10,609
Jake, you're great,

363
00:15:10,642 --> 00:15:13,078
but it's still going
to take a lot of work.

364
00:15:13,111 --> 00:15:14,780
I can get you read,

365
00:15:14,813 --> 00:15:15,981
but you
have to want it,

366
00:15:16,014 --> 00:15:17,616
or it's
a waste of my time.

367
00:15:17,649 --> 00:15:19,718
All right, we'll see.

368
00:15:19,751 --> 00:15:22,587
Do it, or settle for
being a poetry slut,

369
00:15:22,620 --> 00:15:24,123
reading in front
of 20 people.

370
00:15:26,191 --> 00:15:28,126
Look.

371
00:15:28,159 --> 00:15:30,095
My home is on the back.

372
00:15:30,128 --> 00:15:31,730
Get in touch when
you've made up your mind.

373
00:15:33,898 --> 00:15:35,267
Good night.

374
00:15:35,300 --> 00:15:37,002
Okay.

375
00:15:38,737 --> 00:15:40,339
I'll see you.

376
00:15:45,343 --> 00:15:46,712
Thanks, man.

377
00:15:46,745 --> 00:15:49,915
Hey, Gabe,
check this out.

378
00:15:49,948 --> 00:15:51,917
Love to see.

379
00:15:51,950 --> 00:15:54,086
See to love.

380
00:15:54,119 --> 00:15:55,721
To see love.

381
00:15:55,754 --> 00:15:56,855
[Laughs]

382
00:15:56,888 --> 00:15:58,223
You just got laid,
huh?

383
00:15:58,256 --> 00:15:59,257
No.

384
00:15:59,290 --> 00:16:01,026
No.

385
00:16:01,059 --> 00:16:02,493
So, you think
that's any good?

386
00:16:02,527 --> 00:16:03,695
It sucks.

387
00:16:03,728 --> 00:16:05,997
What the hell you
writing about love for?

388
00:16:06,031 --> 00:16:07,699
I mean, why don't
you write about
something you know?

389
00:16:07,732 --> 00:16:09,702
What is that
supposed to mean?

390
00:16:12,237 --> 00:16:14,406
Gabe.

391
00:16:16,441 --> 00:16:19,445
<i> [Tangerine</i> by Eric Miranda
and the plums playing]

392
00:16:30,822 --> 00:16:32,557
♪ I really must be going ♪

393
00:16:32,590 --> 00:16:34,626
♪ no, wait another hour ♪

394
00:16:34,659 --> 00:16:36,461
♪ she's got me never knowing ♪

395
00:16:36,494 --> 00:16:38,196
♪ I'll give her all my power ♪

396
00:16:38,229 --> 00:16:39,831
♪ I sat on a corner ♪

397
00:16:39,864 --> 00:16:41,800
♪ and then
it started raining ♪

398
00:16:41,833 --> 00:16:43,668
♪ you know I just adore her ♪

399
00:16:43,701 --> 00:16:45,971
♪ I'm really not complaining ♪

400
00:16:46,004 --> 00:16:49,475
♪ oh, tangerine ♪

401
00:16:56,448 --> 00:16:59,451
I feed marcello the cat
a can of liver and chicken.

402
00:16:59,484 --> 00:17:01,653
He bolts it down
too fast as usual.

403
00:17:01,686 --> 00:17:04,222
Two minutes later,
he throws up on the back patio.

404
00:17:04,255 --> 00:17:06,525
The first fly shows up
within seconds,

405
00:17:06,558 --> 00:17:09,394
ecstatic over life's bounty.

406
00:17:09,426 --> 00:17:11,195
Within minutes,
the word's out somehow,

407
00:17:11,229 --> 00:17:13,465
the brothers and sisters
coming in fast.

408
00:17:13,498 --> 00:17:15,567
The sun creeps
along the cement floor.

409
00:17:15,599 --> 00:17:17,968
Pretty soon, half
the cat puke is in light,

410
00:17:18,002 --> 00:17:21,072
the other in shadow like
sunrise on a volcanic island.

411
00:17:26,077 --> 00:17:28,280
At least 30 flies
have gathered by now,

412
00:17:28,313 --> 00:17:30,983
walking around and eating
what they're walking around on.

413
00:17:37,956 --> 00:17:39,623
I move in closer.

414
00:17:39,657 --> 00:17:42,561
Such organization and grace.

415
00:17:42,594 --> 00:17:44,062
No fuss, no fighting.

416
00:17:44,095 --> 00:17:47,032
There's obviously always enough
for everyone in the fly world

417
00:17:47,065 --> 00:17:49,535
and plenty of time to get off
a quickie with your neighbor.

418
00:18:05,283 --> 00:18:07,084
I'm now
on my hands and knees,

419
00:18:07,118 --> 00:18:08,986
my face within inches
of the calm feeding

420
00:18:09,020 --> 00:18:10,822
of at least 50 flies,

421
00:18:10,855 --> 00:18:14,059
give or take
arrivals and departures.

422
00:18:14,092 --> 00:18:15,260
None seem to notice me,

423
00:18:15,293 --> 00:18:17,428
the sun glinting
off their emerald thoraxes

424
00:18:17,462 --> 00:18:19,398
and through
their purple wings.

425
00:18:42,654 --> 00:18:43,722
Hey.

426
00:18:43,755 --> 00:18:44,823
Hey.

427
00:18:44,856 --> 00:18:46,191
I'm not sure if
I got the right place.

428
00:18:46,224 --> 00:18:47,826
Uh, marni Elliot
live here?

429
00:18:47,859 --> 00:18:48,960
Yeah, she's here.

430
00:18:48,993 --> 00:18:50,629
She's a little busy
at the moment.

431
00:18:50,662 --> 00:18:53,832
Is there any way I can
talk to her for a second?

432
00:18:53,865 --> 00:18:55,700
Um, she's getting
dressed right now.

433
00:18:55,733 --> 00:18:56,835
I'm sorry.

434
00:18:56,868 --> 00:19:00,705
It's funny that
she told me to come by.

435
00:19:00,738 --> 00:19:02,474
Huh.

436
00:19:02,507 --> 00:19:03,608
I got something
I want to give her.

437
00:19:03,641 --> 00:19:05,610
What, has she
got to sign for it?

438
00:19:05,643 --> 00:19:06,811
Because
I'll give it to her.

439
00:19:06,844 --> 00:19:09,281
No. She don't
gotta sign for it.

440
00:19:09,314 --> 00:19:10,448
Okay.

441
00:19:10,481 --> 00:19:14,519
Just a little,
uh, something that I wrote.

442
00:19:14,552 --> 00:19:16,487
Will you give this to her?

443
00:19:16,521 --> 00:19:18,223
I'll make
sure she gets it.

444
00:19:18,256 --> 00:19:20,058
Well, that's very nice
of you. Thanks.

445
00:19:20,091 --> 00:19:23,395
<i> &quot;cat puke and flies.&quot;</i>

446
00:19:23,428 --> 00:19:24,663
you like that, huh?

447
00:19:24,696 --> 00:19:25,730
It's a good title.

448
00:19:25,763 --> 00:19:27,064
Profound.

449
00:19:27,098 --> 00:19:28,100
Yeah.

450
00:19:31,936 --> 00:19:33,405
Clown.

451
00:19:41,546 --> 00:19:43,748
You see, I like
your hair like that.

452
00:19:43,781 --> 00:19:45,149
I don't know. I'm thinking
about putting it down.

453
00:19:45,183 --> 00:19:46,284
No, no.
It looks good up.

454
00:19:46,317 --> 00:19:47,586
Thank you.

455
00:19:47,619 --> 00:19:50,222
What's this?

456
00:19:50,255 --> 00:19:51,289
Oh, some guy came by,

457
00:19:51,322 --> 00:19:52,857
wanted me to give you
that poem.

458
00:19:52,890 --> 00:19:54,025
Why didn't you get me?

459
00:19:54,058 --> 00:19:55,260
Because I never
interrupt a woman

460
00:19:55,293 --> 00:19:56,628
when she's putting on
her makeup.

461
00:19:56,661 --> 00:19:57,796
Not that you need it.

462
00:19:57,829 --> 00:19:59,231
His name's on it,

463
00:19:59,264 --> 00:20:00,732
unless, of course,
he's too embarrassed.

464
00:20:00,765 --> 00:20:01,900
[Laughs]

465
00:20:01,933 --> 00:20:03,134
He's good.

466
00:20:03,167 --> 00:20:05,203
Totally different style
than yours, though.

467
00:20:05,236 --> 00:20:06,638
Yeah, well, I'll take that
as a compliment.

468
00:20:06,671 --> 00:20:09,774
<i>Cat puke and flies. </i>

469
00:20:09,807 --> 00:20:11,576
Come on.
Let's get out of here.

470
00:20:11,609 --> 00:20:14,178
I need to schedule
something with him.

471
00:20:23,321 --> 00:20:25,724
[Band warming up]

472
00:20:25,757 --> 00:20:27,626
Hello, brother.

473
00:20:27,659 --> 00:20:29,227
What are you guys
doing here?

474
00:20:29,260 --> 00:20:30,562
What's up, pal?

475
00:20:30,595 --> 00:20:31,930
I'm about to
serenade you.

476
00:20:31,963 --> 00:20:34,266
Look behind you.
The boss lady hired me.

477
00:20:36,267 --> 00:20:39,504
Look, I asked etch to put
one of your poems to music.

478
00:20:39,537 --> 00:20:41,940
Really?
Without asking me?

479
00:20:41,973 --> 00:20:43,808
You know, you shouldn't
have to put poetry to music

480
00:20:43,841 --> 00:20:45,243
in order for people
to listen to it.

481
00:20:45,276 --> 00:20:46,611
Look.
It's just an exercise

482
00:20:46,644 --> 00:20:49,114
to get you to learn
about rhythm and phrasing.

483
00:20:49,147 --> 00:20:50,814
Okay?

484
00:20:50,848 --> 00:20:53,351
Okay.
Let's hear it.

485
00:20:53,384 --> 00:20:55,387
[Playing uptempo punk music]

486
00:20:55,420 --> 00:20:57,555
♪ At the precise moment
of death ♪

487
00:20:57,588 --> 00:20:59,924
♪ the pupil in the eye ♪

488
00:20:59,957 --> 00:21:02,427
♪ opens as wide as ♪

489
00:21:03,961 --> 00:21:05,097
♪ the white lies! ♪

490
00:21:08,833 --> 00:21:10,035
Nice.

491
00:21:10,068 --> 00:21:11,703
A prima Donna.

492
00:21:11,736 --> 00:21:14,439
This is bullshit.
You butchered the poem.

493
00:21:14,472 --> 00:21:16,441
They needed to make it
work in a song.

494
00:21:16,474 --> 00:21:18,176
Listen to the rhythm.

495
00:21:18,209 --> 00:21:20,612
How you read a poem
is half the presentation.

496
00:21:22,113 --> 00:21:24,149
I don't need this.

497
00:21:26,617 --> 00:21:29,521
Are you
coming back inside?

498
00:21:29,554 --> 00:21:31,790
Let me do it.

499
00:21:31,823 --> 00:21:33,125
I'll sing it.

500
00:21:34,759 --> 00:21:36,828
[Playing]

501
00:21:36,861 --> 00:21:38,363
Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait!
Yo! Guys!

502
00:21:38,396 --> 00:21:39,764
Guys! Guys!
Hold on! Hold on!

503
00:21:39,797 --> 00:21:41,132
Hold on, hold on.

504
00:21:41,165 --> 00:21:42,600
[Whistles]

505
00:21:42,633 --> 00:21:45,170
Hey. Now, can we slow it down
a little bit, man?

506
00:21:45,203 --> 00:21:46,271
I mean, it's poetry.

507
00:21:46,304 --> 00:21:47,505
Let them hear the words.

508
00:21:47,538 --> 00:21:49,240
All right.
Slow it down.

509
00:21:49,273 --> 00:21:50,742
Bring it down.

510
00:21:50,775 --> 00:21:53,912
[Drummer marking
slow tempo]

511
00:21:53,945 --> 00:21:57,916
♪ At the precise moment
of death ♪

512
00:21:57,949 --> 00:22:05,023
♪ the pupil of the eye
opens wide ♪

513
00:22:05,056 --> 00:22:08,293
♪ the white lights in the sea ♪

514
00:22:08,326 --> 00:22:10,862
♪ the moon, the sun,
and stars ♪

515
00:22:10,895 --> 00:22:13,365
♪ in the sky ♪

516
00:22:15,400 --> 00:22:18,737
♪ the great bend
of the milky way ♪

517
00:22:18,770 --> 00:22:22,706
♪ goes into the fray ♪

518
00:22:22,740 --> 00:22:29,647
♪ there are no lights
too bright for the dying ♪

519
00:22:29,680 --> 00:22:33,585
[Band continues playing]

520
00:22:45,396 --> 00:22:47,432
I was, uh...
I was excited.

521
00:22:47,465 --> 00:22:49,400
I was nervous.

522
00:22:49,434 --> 00:22:51,636
Oddly enough...

523
00:22:52,904 --> 00:22:54,506
