00:51:09,165 --> 00:51:11,067
No. I'm just thinking.

1055
00:51:13,703 --> 00:51:15,105
I like this quilt.

1056
00:51:15,138 --> 00:51:16,840
I've never seen
anything like it before.

1057
00:51:16,873 --> 00:51:18,641
It's an aztec design.

1058
00:51:18,674 --> 00:51:21,578
Sacred quetzal bird.

1059
00:51:21,611 --> 00:51:24,114
Oh, yeah?

1060
00:51:24,147 --> 00:51:26,850
What were you
thinking about?

1061
00:51:26,883 --> 00:51:28,018
Ah.

1062
00:51:29,552 --> 00:51:32,956
I was just thinking
about my brother.

1063
00:51:32,989 --> 00:51:34,624
I wish I could
have known him.

1064
00:51:34,657 --> 00:51:36,426
Yeah.

1065
00:51:36,459 --> 00:51:38,328
He was a good guy.

1066
00:51:39,762 --> 00:51:42,299
He always had
something going on.

1067
00:51:46,269 --> 00:51:50,772
When my parents found out
he was...

1068
00:51:50,806 --> 00:51:52,742
That he was gay, they...

1069
00:51:54,243 --> 00:51:58,615
They immediately sent him
to a psychiatrist.

1070
00:52:00,516 --> 00:52:03,653
It's not their fault.

1071
00:52:03,686 --> 00:52:05,088
They didn't know.

1072
00:52:06,822 --> 00:52:12,262
Well, I gave up
on finding someone.

1073
00:52:12,295 --> 00:52:14,297
I knew David
was wrong for me,

1074
00:52:14,330 --> 00:52:18,334
but at least
he understood.

1075
00:52:18,367 --> 00:52:22,305
Can we not
talk about that guy?

1076
00:52:22,338 --> 00:52:24,908
You're a much better poet.

1077
00:52:24,941 --> 00:52:26,643
Oh, yeah?

1078
00:52:24,941 --> 00:52:26,643
Yeah.

1079
00:52:28,945 --> 00:52:30,880
A better lover, too.

1080
00:52:30,913 --> 00:52:32,415
Oh, yeah.

1081
00:52:30,913 --> 00:52:32,415
Mm-hmm.

1082
00:52:37,153 --> 00:52:38,855
[Blues music playing in bar]

1083
00:52:41,490 --> 00:52:43,158
T.s. Eliot.

1084
00:52:43,192 --> 00:52:46,029
It is t.S., isn't it?

1085
00:52:46,062 --> 00:52:47,697
Give me a beer, t.

1086
00:52:47,730 --> 00:52:50,233
Hey, Benny, why don't
you quit drinking?

1087
00:52:50,266 --> 00:52:53,002
Why don't you quit boring
the shit out of me?

1088
00:52:53,035 --> 00:52:54,571
You know why I drink?

1089
00:52:54,604 --> 00:52:56,573
'Cause it makes assholes
like you more interesting.

1090
00:52:56,606 --> 00:52:57,640
That's why I drink.

1091
00:52:57,673 --> 00:52:58,741
[Chuckles]

1092
00:53:01,444 --> 00:53:02,545
No, chill out.
That's private, man.

1093
00:53:02,578 --> 00:53:03,913
Let me see
what he's writing.

1094
00:53:03,946 --> 00:53:05,482
God.

1095
00:53:10,152 --> 00:53:12,855
&quot;after the war,
my father's hobby
was photography.

1096
00:53:12,888 --> 00:53:15,857
&quot;new fathers often become
photographers, it seems.

1097
00:53:15,891 --> 00:53:18,494
&quot;but he took pictures of
many things besides me,

1098
00:53:18,527 --> 00:53:21,898
&quot;as if he suddenly felt it
all slipping away

1099
00:53:21,931 --> 00:53:23,833
and he wanted
to hold it forever.&quot;

1100
00:53:23,866 --> 00:53:25,168
gosh, that's great.

1101
00:53:25,201 --> 00:53:26,469
Gabe, you see this?

1102
00:53:26,502 --> 00:53:28,904
Yeah. Yeah. But what you
don't understand, youngster,

1103
00:53:28,938 --> 00:53:32,342
is that my man, Benny,
he was the greatest.

1104
00:53:32,375 --> 00:53:34,777
He had a poem published
in<i> the new yorker.</i>

1105
00:53:34,810 --> 00:53:38,047
A major literary success
at 19.

1106
00:53:38,080 --> 00:53:40,817
He was supposed to be
the next Allen Ginsberg.

1107
00:53:40,850 --> 00:53:43,685
From the mouth
of Ginsberg himself.

1108
00:53:43,719 --> 00:53:45,355
Wow.

1109
00:53:45,388 --> 00:53:47,423
So, uh,
what happened to him?

1110
00:53:47,456 --> 00:53:49,659
He felt he could never
live up to that poem again,

1111
00:53:49,692 --> 00:53:51,194
so he never published
anything afterwards.

1112
00:53:51,227 --> 00:53:53,029
Look at this one here.

1113
00:53:53,062 --> 00:53:54,797
[Reading quietly]

1114
00:53:54,830 --> 00:53:56,766
Benny,
this is unbelievable.

1115
00:53:56,799 --> 00:53:59,669
Give me that,
you little twit.

1116
00:53:59,702 --> 00:54:01,638
What? I-I just think
it's really good.

1117
00:54:01,671 --> 00:54:03,071
What the hell would you know?

1118
00:54:03,105 --> 00:54:07,977
Christ sake, that dribble
you write you call poetry?

1119
00:54:08,010 --> 00:54:10,246
I can flatulate
with more feeling.

1120
00:54:10,279 --> 00:54:11,881
Oh, that's funny.

1121
00:54:11,914 --> 00:54:12,983
[Laughing]

1122
00:54:14,216 --> 00:54:15,384
Hey.

1123
00:54:15,418 --> 00:54:16,619
Good news.

1124
00:54:16,652 --> 00:54:18,388
You were accepted
into the poetron slam.

1125
00:54:18,421 --> 00:54:21,290
Really?
Well, that's great.

1126
00:54:21,324 --> 00:54:22,925
Come here.

1127
00:54:22,958 --> 00:54:24,461
What about the beer?

1128
00:54:25,661 --> 00:54:27,397
A rotten goddamn poet,
Gabe,

1129
00:54:27,430 --> 00:54:30,633
and he's
a rotten goddamn bartender.

1130
00:54:30,666 --> 00:54:32,235
A shitty bartender,
but I'm in the, uh...

1131
00:54:32,268 --> 00:54:33,936
I'm in the slam,
Benny.

1132
00:54:33,969 --> 00:54:36,005
The only slam
you're gonna get

1133
00:54:36,038 --> 00:54:37,607
is a goddamn slam dunk.

1134
00:54:37,640 --> 00:54:38,841
Stop it.

1135
00:54:38,874 --> 00:54:40,609
Gabe, check it out.
I got in the poetron slam.

1136
00:54:40,643 --> 00:54:41,978
Yeah, yeah,
congratulations.

1137
00:54:42,011 --> 00:54:45,081
Hey, uh,
how about a break?

1138
00:54:45,114 --> 00:54:47,417
From what?

1139
00:54:50,753 --> 00:54:52,488
Come on. Get up.

1140
00:54:52,521 --> 00:54:53,923
[Groans]

1141
00:54:53,956 --> 00:54:55,291
Let's go, sleepy.

1142
00:54:55,324 --> 00:54:56,793
No.

1143
00:54:56,826 --> 00:54:58,494
Come on. It's time
to step up training.

1144
00:54:58,527 --> 00:55:00,797
I was at the catchword
until 2:00.

1145
00:55:00,830 --> 00:55:02,498
Okay, i'm
going to give you a word.

1146
00:55:02,531 --> 00:55:04,767
I want you to improvise
a poem around the word.

1147
00:55:04,800 --> 00:55:06,536
It's too early
to play this game.

1148
00:55:06,569 --> 00:55:08,204
This isn't a game,
okay?

1149
00:55:08,237 --> 00:55:10,907
The last round of the slam
is improvisation.

1150
00:55:10,940 --> 00:55:12,308
That's where winners
are made.

1151
00:55:12,341 --> 00:55:13,643
I'm not talking
&quot;Roses are red.&quot;

1152
00:55:13,676 --> 00:55:14,977
it should have
all the same complexities

1153
00:55:15,010 --> 00:55:16,679
of your regular poems.

1154
00:55:16,712 --> 00:55:18,014
Metaphors, themes.

1155
00:55:18,047 --> 00:55:20,817
Yeah, yeah, yeah. Allegory,
symbolism, I got it.

1156
00:55:20,850 --> 00:55:21,984
That's right. Okay?

1157
00:55:22,017 --> 00:55:23,919
And improv is
settles' strong suit.

1158
00:55:23,953 --> 00:55:24,887
Mmm.

1159
00:55:24,920 --> 00:55:25,888
Ready?

1160
00:55:25,921 --> 00:55:30,093
Okay.
Um, something easy.

1161
00:55:30,126 --> 00:55:31,394
Sunset.

1162
00:55:31,427 --> 00:55:33,096
Okay,
you have 10 seconds.

1163
00:55:33,129 --> 00:55:34,596
Sunset.

1164
00:55:34,630 --> 00:55:36,099
Okay, um...

1165
00:55:36,132 --> 00:55:39,502
Hmm...sunset, sunset,
sunset, sunset.

1166
00:55:39,535 --> 00:55:40,703
Time's up.

1167
00:55:40,736 --> 00:55:42,305
You couldn't come up
with anything?

1168
00:55:42,338 --> 00:55:43,973
Every greeting card has
a poem about a sunset.

1169
00:55:44,006 --> 00:55:45,674
That wasn't
even 10 seconds,

1170
00:55:45,708 --> 00:55:47,243
and why don't you
give me something I can
work with, you know?

1171
00:55:47,276 --> 00:55:48,944
Like, uh, blood or kill.

1172
00:55:48,978 --> 00:55:50,246
That's more my theme.

1173
00:55:50,279 --> 00:55:52,682
You need to learn
about focus.

1174
00:55:52,715 --> 00:55:54,016
[Seagulls loudly crying]

1175
00:55:52,715 --> 00:55:54,016
At night,

1176
00:55:54,049 --> 00:55:55,585
a man asleep
turns to his life

1177
00:55:55,618 --> 00:55:56,786
and tries to grab it.

1178
00:55:56,819 --> 00:55:58,054
[Jet engines]

1179
00:55:56,819 --> 00:55:58,054
As always,

1180
00:55:58,087 --> 00:56:00,857
it skips just out of
his reach and laughs at him.

1181
00:56:00,890 --> 00:56:04,327
He chases it madly, his feet
heavy as unexploded bombs.

1182
00:56:04,360 --> 00:56:06,929
[Traffic noise]

1183
00:56:04,360 --> 00:56:06,929
Defiantly,
his life dances before him.

1184
00:56:06,962 --> 00:56:08,030
He wants to catch it,

1185
00:56:08,063 --> 00:56:09,799
to run it through
some complicated steps,

1186
00:56:09,832 --> 00:56:11,467
to tango a foxtrot,

1187
00:56:11,500 --> 00:56:13,369
perhaps a mazurka.

1188
00:56:13,402 --> 00:56:14,937
He wants to love his life,

1189
00:56:14,970 --> 00:56:16,705
but it will
have nothing of that

1190
00:56:16,739 --> 00:56:17,874
and only giggles at him,

1191
00:56:17,907 --> 00:56:21,611
[siren]

1192
00:56:17,907 --> 00:56:21,611
Rolling its hips
at a distance.

1193
00:56:21,644 --> 00:56:23,546
I think I lost hearing.

1194
00:56:23,579 --> 00:56:25,581
This was good practice
for you today.

1195
00:56:25,614 --> 00:56:28,951
You know, poets will do
anything to throw you off.

1196
00:56:28,984 --> 00:56:30,586
Scream,
blow whistles,

1197
00:56:30,619 --> 00:56:31,821
stamp their feet,

1198
00:56:31,854 --> 00:56:33,455
anything that's gonna
shake you up.

1199
00:56:33,489 --> 00:56:35,992
Well,
I don't rattle easy.

1200
00:56:36,025 --> 00:56:38,227
Yeah, you're the master
of the chill.

1201
00:56:38,260 --> 00:56:40,129
No, seriously,
I'll be all right.

1202
00:56:40,162 --> 00:56:41,531
You know,
slams at this level,

1203
00:56:41,564 --> 00:56:44,366
they aren't just about words,
but psychological strength.

1204
00:56:44,400 --> 00:56:46,169
I mean, they'll do
anything to crack you,

1205
00:56:46,202 --> 00:56:47,804
make you mispronounce
your words.

1206
00:56:47,837 --> 00:56:49,439
Judges will deduct points
for that.

1207
00:56:49,472 --> 00:56:51,007
Are you sure
you're ready for this?

1208
00:56:51,040 --> 00:56:52,408
Yeah.

1209
00:56:52,441 --> 00:56:54,042
Can we go get
something to eat?

1210
00:56:54,076 --> 00:56:55,945
No. I'm beat.

1211
00:56:55,978 --> 00:56:57,180
Are you sure?
It would be nice to sit down,

1212
00:56:57,213 --> 00:56:59,215
you know, have some food,
glass of wine,

1213
00:56:59,248 --> 00:57:00,783
relax before tomorrow.

1214
00:57:00,816 --> 00:57:01,817
No.

1215
00:57:01,851 --> 00:57:03,419
I don't feel so good.

1216
00:57:03,452 --> 00:57:05,087
Yeah,
you look kind of pale.

1217
00:57:05,120 --> 00:57:06,388
Ohh.

1218
00:57:06,422 --> 00:57:08,357
Marni?

1219
00:57:08,390 --> 00:57:11,094
[Siren]

1220
00:57:15,564 --> 00:57:16,999
Doctor,
here's the chart.

1221
00:57:17,032 --> 00:57:18,901
Dr. Peters?

1222
00:57:18,934 --> 00:57:20,937
Absolutely.

1223
00:57:18,934 --> 00:57:20,937
Okay.

1224
00:57:20,970 --> 00:57:23,473
Yes.

1225
00:57:23,506 --> 00:57:24,774
How's she doing?

1226
00:57:24,807 --> 00:57:26,575
She has a fever
of unknown origin,

1227
00:57:26,609 --> 00:57:28,478
and, uh, her t-cell count
is down.

1228
00:57:28,511 --> 00:57:30,079
We've got her on fluids.

1229
00:57:30,112 --> 00:57:31,747
She needs to rest.

1230
00:57:31,780 --> 00:57:34,016
She has
a pulmonary problem.

1231
00:57:34,049 --> 00:57:37,720
Haven't you ever noticed
her cough?

1232
00:57:37,753 --> 00:57:38,788
Yeah.

1233
00:57:38,821 --> 00:57:40,690
I won't know
whether it's pneumonia

1234
00:57:40,723 --> 00:57:42,058
till we get
her labs back.

1235
00:57:42,091 --> 00:57:43,793
Pneumonia?

1236
00:57:43,826 --> 00:57:47,029
Does that mean now
that she has...

1237
00:57:47,062 --> 00:57:49,298
Aids?

1238
00:57:49,331 --> 00:57:50,666
Let's wait for the labs
to come back.

1239
00:57:50,699 --> 00:57:53,302
It could be common flu,
for all we know.

1240
00:57:53,335 --> 00:57:55,071
Can I talk to her?

1241
00:57:55,104 --> 00:57:57,339
Sure,
but remember what I said.

1242
00:57:57,373 --> 00:57:58,775
She needs to rest.

1243
00:58:03,078 --> 00:58:04,680
How you doing?

1244
00:58:04,713 --> 00:58:05,949
I'm good.

1245
00:58:08,617 --> 00:58:09,686
Jake...

1246
00:58:10,819 --> 00:58:13,256
I used to live with a guy.

1247
00:58:17,826 --> 00:58:21,030
We used to do crystal meth,

1248
00:58:21,063 --> 00:58:23,466
but I didn't know
he used needles.

1249
00:58:23,499 --> 00:58:27,736
By the time I found out,
it was too late for me.

1250
00:58:27,770 --> 00:58:30,439
You don't have to explain
anything to me.

1251
00:58:30,472 --> 00:58:33,376
I want you to know.

1252
00:58:33,409 --> 00:58:36,145
I don't blame anyone else
but myself

1253
00:58:36,178 --> 00:58:37,346
for being HIV-positive.

1254
00:58:37,379 --> 00:58:39,882
It doesn't matter.

1255
00:58:39,915 --> 00:58:41,518
Marni,
it doesn't matter.

1256
00:58:46,922 --> 00:58:48,358
I'm here.

1257
00:58:52,895 --> 00:58:55,064
I want to
be here with you.

1258
00:59:01,570 --> 00:59:02,672
I love you.

1259
00:59:05,774 --> 00:59:08,243
You're still not very good
with improvs.

1260
00:59:16,785 --> 00:59:19,555
I'm gonna take a nap.

1261
00:59:19,588 --> 00:59:20,957
Okay?

1262
00:59:25,527 --> 00:59:26,862
Woman: The beauty comes
from the difficulty,

1263
00:59:26,895 --> 00:59:28,564
the complexity,

1264
00:59:28,597 --> 00:59:31,033
the trap door ever giving way
to other trap door,

1265
00:59:31,066 --> 00:59:33,468
infinite capacity of life.

1266
00:59:33,502 --> 00:59:34,637
It is amazing,

1267
00:59:34,670 --> 00:59:36,472
and the fact that we
survive it is amazing.

1268
00:59:36,505 --> 00:59:39,141
And the fact
that we suffer is beautiful,

1269
00:59:39,174 --> 00:59:41,177
because we are
suffering in jewels.

1270
00:59:41,210 --> 00:59:43,946
We are glittering in the sun
with all the decadent,

1271
00:59:43,979 --> 00:59:47,450
superb richness
of our life's experience

1272
00:59:47,483 --> 00:59:49,418
dripping from our fingers

1273
00:59:49,451 --> 00:59:52,421
and our wrists
and the tips of our hair.

1274
00:59:52,454 --> 00:59:55,658
And when we leave this world
and walk into the opal light

1275
00:59:55,691 --> 00:59:57,759
that we have come
to think of as god,

1276
00:59:57,793 --> 01:00:00,096
we will not go naked.

1277
01:00:00,129 --> 01:00:02,031
We will go
glittering.

1278
01:00:02,064 --> 01:00:04,767
The poem list
looks great.

1279
01:00:04,800 --> 01:00:07,169
There's just something
missing.

1280
01:00:07,202 --> 01:00:08,237
Did you get
what I asked for?

1281
01:00:17,780 --> 01:00:20,383
I didn't like doing it.

1282
01:00:20,416 --> 01:00:22,284
The slam material
has to be original.

1283
01:00:22,317 --> 01:00:24,086
Look,
don't worry about that.

1284
01:00:24,119 --> 01:00:25,554
It's not right.

1285
01:00:25,587 --> 01:00:27,123
Great imagery.

1286
01:00:27,156 --> 01:00:29,725
Who is this guy,
anyway?

1287
01:00:29,758 --> 01:00:33,395
He's a genius that looks and
sounds like a pile of garbage.

1288
01:00:33,429 --> 01:00:35,264
I buy some stuff from him
every once in a while.

1289
01:00:35,297 --> 01:00:37,099
You can win without it.

1290
01:00:37,132 --> 01:00:39,435
I got a lot riding on tomorrow,
and so do you.

1291
01:00:39,468 --> 01:00:42,004
If I succeed, you succeed,
so don't sweat it.

1292
01:00:42,037 --> 01:00:44,540
What, all
we need's a couple
of mispronounced words?

1293
01:00:44,573 --> 01:00:45,941
That's right.

1294
01:00:45,974 --> 01:00:48,644
And I got a plan
that's gonna take him down.

1295
01:00:48,677 --> 01:00:51,214
He's gonna throw his poem list
right out the window.

1296
01:00:53,916 --> 01:00:55,118
It's going to be all right.

1297
01:01:05,861 --> 01:01:09,198
What are you doing?

1298
01:01:09,231 --> 01:01:10,700
I got up an hour ago.

1299
01:01:10,733 --> 01:01:12,902
I took a shower
to let you sleep.

1300
01:01:12,935 --> 01:01:14,837
Come on. Let's get you home
and out of those clothes.

1301
01:01:14,870 --> 01:01:16,305
Wait a minute,
wait a minute,
wait a minute.

1302
01:01:16,338 --> 01:01:17,640
You're sick.

1303
01:01:17,673 --> 01:01:19,475
You can't
just get up and walk
out of the hospital.

1304
01:01:19,508 --> 01:01:22,544
I'm not missing this
for anything, okay?

1305
01:01:22,578 --> 01:01:24,013
I awakened this morning.

1306
01:01:24,046 --> 01:01:25,714
I was filled with despair.

1307
01:01:25,748 --> 01:01:27,583
Darkness surrounded me.

1308
01:01:27,616 --> 01:01:30,453
Death hung heavy
on my shoulders.

1309
01:01:30,486 --> 01:01:32,321
I saw no reason to live.

1310
01:01:32,354 --> 01:01:34,622
And then, I remembered
what today held.

1311
01:01:34,656 --> 01:01:36,558
I saw a window of light,

1312
01:01:36,592 --> 01:01:37,993
a reason to be.

1313
01:01:38,026 --> 01:01:39,428
And now, I'm here.

1314
01:01:39,461 --> 01:01:42,631
Welcome to the Los Angeles
poetron slam!

1315
01:01:47,136 --> 01:01:49,205
Today, the finest poets
on the west coast

1316
01:01:49,238 --> 01:01:52,808
will compete
for a $25,000 cash prize,

1317
01:01:52,841 --> 01:01:56,912
plus a paid series of readings,
a spoken word cd contract,

1318
01:01:56,945 --> 01:01:59,815
and a publishing deal
by our wonderful sponsors,

1319
01:01:59,848 --> 01:02:01,116
windsor house press,

1320
01:02:01,150 --> 01:02:04,286
represented here today
by Mr. Marc neihauser!

1321
01:02:04,319 --> 01:02:05,988
[Applause]

1322
01:02:06,021 --> 01:02:08,557
Welcome, Marc!

1323
01:02:08,590 --> 01:02:10,159
And now,
from out of the west,

1324
01:02:10,192 --> 01:02:12,628
come the thundering hoofbeats
of our first contestant.

1325
01:02:12,661 --> 01:02:17,700
From the tumbleweed world
of cowboy poetry, Fresno Pete!

1326
01:02:17,733 --> 01:02:20,336
[Applause]

1327
01:02:17,733 --> 01:02:20,336
Yee-ha!

1328
01:02:20,369 --> 01:02:22,872
There's two things in life
I really love.

1329
01:02:22,905 --> 01:02:25,207
That's women and horses.

1330
01:02:25,240 --> 01:02:27,142
This, I'm sure of.

1331
01:02:27,176 --> 01:02:31,514
So when I die,
you please tan my hide

1332
01:02:31,547 --> 01:02:35,117
and tool me
into a saddle so fine

1333
01:02:35,150 --> 01:02:38,721
and give me to a cowgirl
who likes to ride,

1334
01:02:38,754 --> 01:02:40,156
so in the hereafter,

1335
01:02:40,189 --> 01:02:42,258
I may rest

1336
01:02:42,291 --> 01:02:45,594
between the two things
I love the best.

1337
01:02:45,627 --> 01:02:48,764
Woman:
You tell 'em, cowboy!

1338
01:02:48,797 --> 01:02:50,266
Longfellow:
Thank you, Pete.

1339
01:02:50,299 --> 01:02:52,668
There's a real man, who makes
plans for sex even after death.

1340
01:02:52,701 --> 01:02:54,570
Now, let's check in
with our esteemed judges.

1341
01:02:54,603 --> 01:02:57,106
[Applause]

1342
01:02:57,139 --> 01:02:58,474
Good work, partner.

1343
01:02:58,507 --> 01:03:00,276
And now, it's high noon.

1344
01:03:00,309 --> 01:03:03,512
And here's a man who has
a showdown with a cowboy poet,

1345
01:03:03,545 --> 01:03:04,580
Jake Thompson!

1346
01:03:04,613 --> 01:03:05,982
Man: Yeah!

1347
01:03:09,484 --> 01:03:11,354
Let's see what you got,
poetry boy.

1348
01:03:12,921 --> 01:03:15,424
&quot;how many fights have
you been in?&quot; She asks,

1349
01:03:15,457 --> 01:03:17,993
holding my hand,

1350
01:03:18,026 --> 01:03:21,931
running a painted fingernail
around big, angry knuckles,

1351
01:03:21,964 --> 01:03:24,933
rubbing faint, pink scars,
as if to make a wish.

1352
01:03:24,967 --> 01:03:27,937
Spreading fingers wide,
I show her my digits,

1353
01:03:27,970 --> 01:03:30,538
all twisted and bent
with the force of impact!

1354
01:03:30,572 --> 01:03:31,674
Man: Yeah!

1355
01:03:31,707 --> 01:03:36,011
&quot;just one,&quot;
I say to her,

1356
01:03:36,044 --> 01:03:38,013
&quot;and I'm getting
my ass kicked.&quot;

1357
01:03:38,046 --> 01:03:39,816
[applause]

1358
01:03:46,655 --> 01:03:49,291
Least I lost to something
I understand.

1359
01:03:49,324 --> 01:03:50,593
All right, man.
Take care.

1360
01:03:52,861 --> 01:03:55,663
That felt so good.
I can't believe it.

1361
01:03:55,697 --> 01:03:57,766
They're not all going
to be that easy, okay?

1362
01:03:57,799 --> 01:03:59,101
You have to keep
your level up.

1363
01:03:59,134 --> 01:04:00,302
I want you
to look at the judges.

1364
01:04:00,335 --> 01:04:02,204
Are you okay?

1365
01:04:00,335 --> 01:04:02,204
I'm fine.

1366
01:04:02,237 --> 01:04:03,205
Don't worry about me.

1367
01:04:03,238 --> 01:04:04,673
Worry about the competition.

1368
01:04:04,706 --> 01:04:07,977
Next up is a man
who never rides sidesaddle,

1369
01:04:08,010 --> 01:04:10,246
chrome Harley.

1370
01:04:10,279 --> 01:04:11,480
Woman: Yeah, baby!

1371
01:04:11,513 --> 01:04:14,750
Vroom! Vroom! Vroom!
You're ready to move!

1372
01:04:14,783 --> 01:04:18,754
Scour oily hand,
comb hair smooth.

1373
01:04:18,787 --> 01:04:21,457
Pull out all 8 glistening feet
of hand-polished

1374
01:04:21,490 --> 01:04:25,394
heaven reflection,
petted to perfection.

1375
01:04:25,427 --> 01:04:27,029
Vroom! Vroom! Vroom!

1376
01:04:27,062 --> 01:04:30,065
The power to part traffic
like a modernized Moses.

1377
01:04:30,098 --> 01:04:32,534
Other drivers know
a monster-style machine

1378
01:04:32,567 --> 01:04:33,702
when they see one.

1379
01:04:33,735 --> 01:04:35,337
[Applause]

1380
01:04:35,370 --> 01:04:38,774
They say in the flattest
part of north Dakota

1381
01:04:38,807 --> 01:04:41,509
on a starless,
moonless night,

1382
01:04:41,543 --> 01:04:42,811
no breath of wind,

1383
01:04:42,844 --> 01:04:47,049
a man can light a candle
and walk away.

1384
01:04:47,082 --> 01:04:48,517
And every now and then,

1385
01:04:48,550 --> 01:04:51,053
he can turn and
see the candle burning.

1386
01:04:51,086 --> 01:04:52,388
17 miles later,

1387
01:04:52,421 --> 01:04:55,691
provided the conditions
remained ideal,

1388
01:04:55,724 --> 01:04:57,660
he could
still see the flame.

1389
01:04:57,693 --> 01:05:00,396
Somewhere between
the 17th and 18th mile,

1390
01:05:00,429 --> 01:05:02,097
he would lose sight
of the flame.

1391
01:05:02,130 --> 01:05:03,799
If he were walking backwards,

1392
01:05:03,832 --> 01:05:06,134
he would know
the exact moment he lost it.

1393
01:05:06,168 --> 01:05:09,038
He could take a step forward
and find it again.

1394
01:05:09,071 --> 01:05:10,572
Back and forth,

1395
01:05:10,605 --> 01:05:12,341
dark to light,

1396
01:05:12,374 --> 01:05:13,808
light to dark.

1397
01:05:13,842 --> 01:05:17,046
What is this place
where the light disappears?

1398
01:05:17,079 --> 01:05:19,748
Where it reappears?

1399
01:05:19,781 --> 01:05:22,084
Don't tell me
about eyeballs and photons,

1400
01:05:22,117 --> 01:05:23,752
reflection, refraction.

1401
01:05:23,785 --> 01:05:26,587
Don't tell me about
186,000 miles per second,

1402
01:05:26,621 --> 01:05:28,257
the theory of relativity.

1403
01:05:28,290 --> 01:05:31,393
Because all I know
is that place

1404
01:05:31,426 --> 01:05:35,163
where the light appears
and disappears,

1405
01:05:35,197 --> 01:05:37,866
that's the place
where we live.

1406
01:05:37,899 --> 01:05:42,371
[Applause]

1407
01:05:46,575 --> 01:05:47,910
Yes!

1408
